The paper proposes a visualization approach for hyperspectral imagery, which involves learning a visualized image that preserves the manifold structure of the HSI while having natural colors. This involves applying a composite kernel to incorporate both spatial and spectral information, and constraining the colors of the output image based on a natural-looking RGB image. The paper also discusses instance-level and feature-level learning. Based on these details, the most likely sub-categories are computer vision (cs.CV), graphics (cs.GR), and machine learning (cs.LG). Multimedia (cs.MM) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) are also possible sub-categories given the focus on learning and information preservation.
